title: For Sale:  Marlin .30-30 Rifle, Model 336CS, with Scope
postcontent:
To help settle an estate, I'm selling a Marlin Model 336CS, Lever Action .30-30 Rifle, with a Tasco Pronghorn 4x30 scope mounted on Weaver see-through rings.  The iron sights are visible through the scope mount.  

This older rifle is in perfect mechanical condition, and has obviously been shot very little, but long-term storage has caused some damage to the finish.  There are a few small bare spots on the barrel, and the left side of the receiver.  Some of the finish it also gone on the tops of the Weaver scope rings.  There is no rust on the gun.  It's a working gun you can throw in the truck and take to the woods without worrying about marring the finish.

This 336CS is the deluxe model with a checkered walnut stock and grip cap, and features the cross bolt safety.  The stock is a beautiful piece of walnut, with nice sharp cut checkering.  It has a rubber rifle butt pad, and a blued steel barrel band with integral swivel stud.

Since its introduction in 1948, the Marlin 336 family has been one of the most popular hunting rifles in North America.  Over 6 million Model 336 rifles have been produced.  It embodies Marlin's dedication to dependability, pinpoint accuracy and good looks.  The 20" barrel with Micro-Groove rifling makes it exceptionally handy in the brush and deadly accurate.  

This Marlin has been in storage for many years and is now available for sale.  The asking price of $350 is fair for a sturdy scoped rifle in this condition.  Deer season is upon us.  Don't be bashful. Contact me and let's talk about this gun. It would be the perfect Christmas gift for someone special.

title: For Sale:  Heckler & Koch MR556A1 Rifle
location: Goldsboro, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
HK MR556A1
Barrel Length: 16.5"
Caliber: 5.56MM
Color: Black
Sights: None

A direct descendent of the HK416, the MR556A1 is a semi-automatic rifle developed by Heckler & Koch as a premium level commercial/civilian firearm with match rifle capability. Like the HK416, the MR556A1 is a major product improvement over conventional AR-type carbines and rifles.

The MR556A1 uses the HK proprietary gas piston operating system, employing a piston and a solid operating “pusher” rod in place of the gas tube normally found in AR15/M16/M4-style firearms.

This method of operation virtually eliminates malfunctions that are common to direct impingement gas systems since hot carbon fouling and waste gases do not enter the receiver area. This is the same key feature critical to the success of the HK416 rifles used by leading military and law enforcement customers.

The MR556A1 is produced in the USA using American and German made components. The MR556A1 uses many of the same assemblies and accessories originally developed for the HK416 including the HK free-floating four-quadrant rail system.

The HK Free Floating Rail System (FFRS) handguard has four MIL-STD-1913 “Picatinny” rails and allows all current accessories, sights, lights, and aimers used on M4/M16-type arms to be fitted to the MR Series. The HK rail system can be installed and removed with simple tools and returns to zero when reinstalled.

The MR556A1 also has a Picantinny rail machined into the top of its upper receiver for mounting optics and mechanical sights. Unlike earlier prototypes, major subassemblies, including the MR556A1 upper receiver/barrel assembly, are fully interchangeable with other high quality AR-style firearms. MR556A1 upper receiver kits can be used to retrofit competing legacy AR systems.

Like the famous HK416, the MR556A1 uses a German-made barrel produced by Heckler & Koch’s famous cold hammer forging process. The highest quality steel is used in this unique manufacturing process producing a barrel that provides superior accuracy and long service life.

But unlike the HK416, the MR556A1 does not use a chrome-lined barrel. Chrome-lining can sometimes mask bore imperfections and negatively affect accuracy. For the new series of Heckler & Koch semi-automatic MR rifles, HK designers and engineers believe best accuracy comes with an unlined bore.

Used with the HK Free Floating Rail System, the barrel does not touch the handguard, ensuring the barrel is truly free-floating for maximum accuracy.

The unchromed barrel has an internal profile of 6 lands and grooves with a 1 in 7 inch (178 mm) twist. It is also moderately “swagged” with a slightly smaller internal diameter at the muzzle end than the chamber end. This feature has a positive effect on bullet accuracy and velocity. The thick, heavy contour 16.5-inch MR556A1 barrel also contributes to its excellent accuracy.

A precise enhanced two-stage trigger adds significantly to the accuracy of the MR556A1 and an extended latch charging handle makes operating the rifle with a telescopic sight easier. The retractable buttstock can be locked into a solid, non-moving position by tightening an Allen screw in the bottom of the stock. Special target rifle takedown pins ensure the upper and lower receivers are firmly mated for accurate performance.

Designed to function with a wide variety of high quality 5.56 x 45 mm ammunition, the MR556A1 uses a C.I.P. dimensioned chamber (a chamber with dimensions specified by the Commission Internationale Permanente).The MR556A1 also functions reliably with most quality Caliber .223 Remington ammunition.

The MR556A1 is being produced with the same commitment to quality as German-made HK firearms. By using joint U.S./German manufacturing, Heckler & Koch leverages the relative strengths of two continents to make the preeminent AR-type firearm, combining the designs innovations of the USA and Germany into one new product.

title: For Sale/Trade:  CZ P-09 9mm
location: Cliffdale Rd area, Fayetteville, North Carolina
postcontent:
I'm selling my 2013 model CZ P-09 only to raise money for another shooting project...otherwise, this gun has been very good to me and runs GREAT.  It is the first 9mm handgun I purchased and pretty much what I used to learn to shoot a "big gun" (my other was a .22 plinker).  I did a lot of research before buying this gun and it's been a fantastic firearm.

Billed as a "duty" or service gun, this is a full size (4.53" barrel) 19+1 9mm pistol.  The Czechs have long been known for quality firearms and this is no exception.  The slide milling is beautiful; the barrel's feed ramp is mirror polished.  I have probably somewhere between 600 and 800 rounds through it and it has not failed a single time...no failures to load, fire, extract, or eject.  It just runs like a clock.  Almost everything I shoot through it is 115 grain Winchester "white box" ammo...the cheap stuff.  Either that or 115 grain Blazer Brass or Federal.  It eats everything I've run through it.

I changed out the stock recoil spring (18#) for a lighter one (13#) to make sure there are no problems with lighter loads.  The stiffer spring seems to work better for the stouter loads.  I am certainly including BOTH springs with the gun, so you can tune it yourself to what you want to shoot.

Features: it's a hammer-fired gun with the double action-to-single action mechanism.  It has CZ's really versatile Omega trigger system, and actually comes with the parts to convert the gun to a manual safety instead of the "hammer drop" decocker lever.  I've run both on this gun to see what I like best, and I have the decocker lever on it now.  I will show you the steps to take to convert it to manual safety if that is what you prefer.  It takes about 5 minutes...there are videos on YouTube as well.

It comes with all of the original paperwork and all of the original materials.  I bought it in January 2014 for $499+tax at Shooter's Supply on Bragg Blvd.  It was the only P-09 I could find in town at the time.  They're still somewhat hard to find locally (the smaller P-07 is more common).  The materials include the nice CZ case, the factory target calibration paper, the two additional backstraps (small and large; it has the medium installed), the cleaning brush and rod, and the two factory magazines.  Disclosure: the magazines are 19 round magazines, but I can only cram 18 rounds in them.  In addition to what's listed above, you also get the "Special Collector's Edition 2014" of Guns and Ammo magazine, which is dedicated to coverage of CZ's excellent products, with a nice cover story about the P-09.

I'm looking to sell for cash to buy a S&W M&P 9.  If you have an M&P 9 that you would like to trade, please contact me.

Email me with any questions; my email goes straight to my phone, and I'll answer back as soon as I can.  Buyer needs to have either a North Carolina Pistol Purchase Permit to surrender to me or a North Carolina Concealed Handgun Permit that I can photocopy or photograph for my records, and to go along with the Bill of Sale.

Thank you for looking, and have a great day.

The PF-9 retains the best features from our P-11 and P-3AT pistols combined into the flattest and lightest single stack 9mm configuration ever made. The barrel, locking system, slide stop, assembly pin, front sight, recoil springs and guide rod are adapted from the P-11. The PF-9 is nearly identical to the P-11 in length and height and shares the same exterior controls. The shorter trigger system with integral hammer block and the extraction system are adapted from the P-3AT. Just like the P-11, the PF-9 will accept +P ammunition, however, not with continuous use.

postcontent:
Thank you for looking!

For sale today, we have a Springfield XD-40 Tactical with 5" barrel, stainless steel Stormlake 9mm barrel, two 16-round 9mm magazines, four 10-round .40 S&W magazines, and one 12-round .40 S&W magazine.

The Stormlake 9mm barrel is designed to give you drop-in conversion to a 5" 9mm barrel, using the same slide and recoil spring.  When you want to switch, you simply take off the slide, pull the spring, swap the barrel, and reassemble.

The Springfield XD-40 Tactical is a striker-fired semi-auto with 5" barrel, accessory rail, and grip safety.  It features a loaded-chamber indicator on top and a striker-charged indicator on the back.  Takedown is fast and easy using the side lever.  Springfield's XD series is clearly Glock inspired, and it's known for excellent reliability and accuracy.

This gun is in good physical condition, with some minor holster wear.  It has white lettering as can be seen in the pictures.  It gets compliments, but if you prefer to go back to original, it's easily removed with non-acetone nail polish remover.

My wife and I both love this gun, and we hate to let it go, but she carries a slim 9mm gun, and I carry a higher-capacity hammer-fired gun.  The Springfield usually ends up coming to the range with us, but it rarely ends up as our carry-guns.  Facing that fact, we've decided to let it go for someone who is looking for a quality piece.

It has never given us ANY issue.  Even shooting low-power reloaded 9mm didn't cause any FTF, FTE, or anything!  It just keeps running whatever we give it.  The recoil is so gentle, making it fun to practice for extended periods of time.  The long sight radius makes even rifle-range targets fun to hit.  We have always kept it clean, and this last trip out to the range I disassembled the striker assembly and cleaned that as well.
